# CATEGORY 2: Adversarial Attack Demonstrations (40)
# =============================================================================
rows.append(("What was the road sign adversarial attack demonstration?","Researchers at the University of Washington showed in 2017 that placing small stickers on stop signs caused deep neural networks to misclassify them as speed limit signs with up to 100% confidence. The perturbations were designed to be inconspicuous to humans but exploited the model's learned feature representations, demonstrating real-world adversarial vulnerability in autonomous driving."))
rows.append(("How did adversarial glasses fool facial recognition systems?","In 2016, researchers at Carnegie Mellon University demonstrated that specially patterned eyeglass frames could cause facial recognition systems to misidentify the wearer as a different person. The adversarial patterns, printed on the glasses, were optimized to shift the neural network's embedding of the wearer's face to match a target identity with high confidence."))
rows.append(("What was the 3D-printed turtle adversarial example?","In 2018, MIT researchers from the LabSix group demonstrated that a 3D-printed turtle with an adversarial texture was consistently classified as a rifle by Google's InceptionV3 image classifier from multiple angles and distances. This showed adversarial examples could work in the physical 3D world, not just on 2D digital images."))
rows.append(("How do adversarial patches on clothing work?","Researchers have demonstrated T-shirts and patches with adversarial patterns that can fool person detection systems. A 2020 study from KU Leuven showed printed patches that could make pedestrians invisible to YOLO object detectors, raising concerns about adversaries evading surveillance systems using physically realizable adversarial wearables."))
rows.append(("What are audio adversarial examples against voice assistants?","Researchers at UC Berkeley in 2018 demonstrated that inaudible or near-inaudible audio perturbations could be embedded in music or speech to issue hidden commands to voice assistants like Siri and Alexa. The adversarial audio was imperceptible to humans but reliably triggered specific actions on the target devices."))
rows.append(("How have adversarial text attacks targeted spam filters?","Adversarial text attacks against spam filters use character substitutions (e.g., replacing letters with visually similar Unicode characters), word insertions, and paraphrasing to evade detection. Studies have shown that even adding a single carefully chosen word to a phishing email can flip a spam classifier's decision from spam to legitimate with high probability."))
rows.append(("What was the Adversarial Patch attack by Brown et al.?","In 2017, Tom Brown and colleagues demonstrated that a single universal adversarial patch—a printed image—could be placed anywhere in a scene and cause classifiers to output a chosen target class regardless of the actual scene content. The patch worked in the physical world and did not need to overlap with the target object, making it a practical attack vector."))
rows.append(("How did researchers demonstrate adversarial attacks on medical imaging AI?","In 2019, researchers showed they could add imperceptible perturbations to CT scans that caused AI diagnostic systems to either add or remove evidence of lung cancer with near-perfect success rates. In a blinded study, radiologists reviewing the modified scans were fooled 99% of the time, highlighting critical security concerns for AI in healthcare."))
rows.append(("What are transferability-based adversarial attacks?","Adversarial examples crafted against one model often fool other models trained on the same task, a property called transferability. Papernot et al. demonstrated in 2016 that adversarial examples generated against a known surrogate model could be used as black-box attacks against unknown target models, making adversarial attacks practical even without access to the target system."))
rows.append(("What was the DeepFool adversarial attack method?","DeepFool, introduced by Moosavi-Dezfooli et al. in 2016, computed minimal perturbations needed to change a classifier's output by finding the closest decision boundary. It demonstrated that the robustness of deep networks was much lower than previously assumed, with perturbations often imperceptible to humans being sufficient to change classifications."))
rows.append(("How did researchers attack autonomous vehicle LiDAR systems?","In 2019, researchers from the University of Michigan showed that spoofing LiDAR sensors with carefully timed laser pulses could inject fake obstacles or remove real ones from an autonomous vehicle's perception. The attack could create phantom vehicles or make real pedestrians invisible to the car's 3D perception system."))
rows.append(("What are universal adversarial perturbations?","Moosavi-Dezfooli et al. demonstrated in 2017 that a single, image-agnostic perturbation pattern could cause misclassification across a large majority of natural images when added to them. This universal perturbation was small enough to be imperceptible and worked across different images, making it more dangerous than instance-specific attacks."))
rows.append(("How were adversarial examples used to evade malware detection?","Researchers demonstrated that adversarial modifications to malware binaries—such as appending benign code segments or modifying unused header fields—could evade ML-based malware classifiers while preserving malicious functionality. A 2017 study showed evasion rates exceeding 60% against commercial antivirus systems using gradient-based perturbations."))
rows.append(("What is the Fast Gradient Sign Method (FGSM) attack?","FGSM, introduced by Goodfellow, Shlens, and Szegedy in 2015, generates adversarial examples by computing the gradient of the loss function with respect to the input and adding a small perturbation in the direction of the gradient's sign. It is computationally cheap and demonstrated that adversarial vulnerability is a fundamental property of linear models, not just deep networks."))
rows.append(("How did adversarial attacks target natural language processing models?","TextFooler (Jin et al., 2020) showed that replacing a small number of words with semantically similar synonyms could cause state-of-the-art NLP models including BERT to misclassify text with over 90% success rate. The perturbed text remained grammatically correct and semantically similar to humans, making detection difficult."))
rows.append(("What was demonstrated about adversarial robustness of commercial cloud AI APIs?","In 2020, researchers tested adversarial examples against commercial image classification APIs from Google Cloud Vision, Amazon Rekognition, and Microsoft Azure. They found that simple adversarial perturbations generated against open-source models transferred successfully to these commercial systems, demonstrating that even production-grade AI services were vulnerable."))
rows.append(("How did researchers attack facial recognition used for payment systems?","In 2019, researchers demonstrated that adversarial makeup patterns applied to a person's face could fool Alipay and WeChat's facial recognition payment systems. The carefully designed makeup, which appeared as normal cosmetic patterns to humans, shifted the face embedding enough to either deny the legitimate user or impersonate a target identity."))
rows.append(("What is the Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) attack?","PGD, formalized by Madry et al. in 2018, is an iterative version of FGSM that applies multiple small gradient steps while projecting back onto an epsilon-ball around the original input. It is widely considered the strongest first-order adversarial attack and became the standard benchmark for evaluating adversarial robustness of neural networks."))
rows.append(("How were adversarial examples demonstrated against reinforcement learning agents?","Huang et al. (2017) showed that adversarial perturbations to observations could cause trained reinforcement learning agents, including those playing Atari games, to take catastrophically wrong actions. A small perturbation to a single frame could cause the agent to lose a game it would otherwise win, raising concerns about RL deployment in safety-critical control systems."))
rows.append(("What are backdoor attacks on neural networks?","Backdoor attacks, demonstrated by Gu et al. in 2017 (BadNets), involve poisoning training data to create a hidden trigger that activates a specific misclassification. For example, a stop sign recognition model could be trained to classify stop signs with a small yellow sticker as speed limit signs while performing normally on clean inputs."))
rows.append(("How did adversarial attacks target automatic speech recognition?","Carlini and Wagner demonstrated in 2018 that they could craft audio waveforms that sounded like normal speech or music to humans but were transcribed as arbitrary target phrases by DeepSpeech, Mozilla's speech recognition system. The adversarial audio had less than 0.1 dB distortion, making it virtually indistinguishable from the original."))
rows.append(("What are model inversion attacks?","Fredrikson et al. demonstrated in 2015 that given access to a facial recognition model's API, an attacker could reconstruct recognizable images of the training data subjects. By optimizing an input image to maximize the model's confidence for a target class, they recovered face images that were identifiable by human observers, demonstrating a serious privacy risk."))
rows.append(("How did researchers demonstrate adversarial attacks on self-driving car object detection?","In 2020, researchers showed that adversarial billboards placed alongside roads could cause object detection models used in autonomous vehicles to miss pedestrians in the scene entirely. The billboard's adversarial pattern suppressed pedestrian detections in the surrounding area, creating a dangerous blind spot for the vehicle's perception system."))
rows.append(("What is the Carlini & Wagner (C&W) L2 attack?","The C&W attack, published by Carlini and Wagner in 2017, reformulated adversarial example generation as an optimization problem that minimized perturbation size while guaranteeing misclassification. It defeated defensive distillation, the best defense at the time, with 100% success rate and became the gold standard for evaluating adversarial defenses."))
rows.append(("How have adversarial attacks been demonstrated against content moderation AI?","Researchers showed that adversarial perturbations to images containing policy-violating content (violence, nudity) could cause content moderation AI to classify them as safe. Techniques included adding subtle noise patterns, slight geometric transformations, or overlay patterns that preserved the harmful content's visibility to humans while evading automated detection."))
rows.append(("What are data poisoning attacks on machine learning?","Data poisoning attacks involve injecting malicious samples into a model's training data to manipulate its behavior. Biggio et al. (2012) showed that poisoning just 3% of training data could degrade an SVM spam filter's accuracy significantly. Later work showed targeted poisoning could cause specific misclassifications while maintaining overall accuracy to avoid detection."))
rows.append(("How did adversarial examples target document OCR systems?","Researchers demonstrated that adding nearly invisible perturbations to printed documents could cause OCR systems to misread text while remaining perfectly legible to humans. A 2020 study showed that adversarial modifications to invoices and checks could change recognized amounts or account numbers, posing risks for automated document processing pipelines."))
rows.append(("What are semantic adversarial examples?","Unlike pixel-level perturbations, semantic adversarial examples use meaningful transformations like changes in lighting, rotation, or color shifts. Hosseini and Poovendran (2018) showed that simple color space manipulations that appeared natural to humans could fool image classifiers, suggesting that adversarial vulnerability extends beyond artificial noise patterns."))
rows.append(("How were adversarial attacks demonstrated against satellite image analysis?","Researchers showed in 2019 that adversarial patches placed on rooftops or ground surfaces could fool satellite image classification systems used for military intelligence and urban planning. The patches could make buildings invisible to detection algorithms or cause misclassification of terrain types, with implications for national security applications."))
rows.append(("What is the Expectation Over Transformation (EOT) attack method?","Athalye et al. introduced EOT in 2018 to generate adversarial examples robust to physical-world transformations like viewing angle changes, lighting variations, and camera noise. By optimizing adversarial perturbations over a distribution of expected transformations, they created 3D adversarial objects that fooled classifiers reliably in the real world."))

