rows.append(("What was the ChatGPT conversation data leak of March 2023?","On March 20, 2023, OpenAI disclosed a bug in ChatGPT that allowed some users to see titles from other users' chat histories and, in some cases, payment information of ChatGPT Plus subscribers. The bug was caused by a race condition in the Redis client library, and OpenAI took ChatGPT offline for several hours to fix it. Approximately 1.2% of Plus subscribers may have had payment data exposed."))
rows.append(("How did Samsung employees leak confidential code via an LLM?","In April 2023, Samsung semiconductor employees pasted confidential source code, internal meeting notes, and hardware test data into ChatGPT on at least three separate occasions within 20 days. Samsung subsequently banned all generative AI tool usage on company devices and networks, and began developing an internal LLM alternative."))
rows.append(("What was the Clearview AI data breach?","In February 2020, Clearview AI disclosed that its entire client list was stolen by an intruder who exploited a software vulnerability. The breach exposed the list of law enforcement agencies and private companies using the controversial facial recognition service, which had scraped over 3 billion images from the internet without consent."))
rows.append(("How was training data extracted from GPT-2?","In 2020, Carlini et al. demonstrated that GPT-2 had memorized and could regurgitate verbatim text from its training data, including personally identifiable information, URLs, and code snippets. By generating large volumes of text and using membership inference techniques, they extracted hundreds of memorized training examples, revealing significant privacy risks in large language models."))
rows.append(("What privacy violations occurred with Flo Health's AI period tracker?","In January 2021, the FTC settled with Flo Health after the company shared intimate health data from its AI-powered period and fertility tracking app with Facebook, Google, and other analytics firms, contrary to its privacy promises. The app had over 100 million downloads, and users' sensitive reproductive health data was used for targeted advertising."))
rows.append(("What was the Microsoft AI research data exposure incident?","In September 2023, Microsoft's AI research team accidentally exposed 38 terabytes of private data through a misconfigured Azure SAS token shared in a GitHub repository. The exposed data included private keys, passwords, internal Teams messages, and backups of two employees' workstations, demonstrating risks of sharing AI training data through cloud storage."))
rows.append(("How did model extraction attacks compromise commercial ML services?","Tramer et al. demonstrated in 2016 that machine learning models deployed via prediction APIs (including those by Amazon and BigML) could be stolen through systematic queries. By making a polynomial number of queries, they reconstructed functionally equivalent copies of logistic regression, decision tree, and neural network models, exposing intellectual property."))
rows.append(("What privacy issues arose with AI-powered proctoring software during COVID-19?","During the 2020-2021 remote learning period, AI proctoring tools like Proctorio and ExamSoft collected extensive biometric data including facial recordings, keystroke patterns, and eye movement data from millions of students. Multiple data breaches and privacy complaints were filed, and studies showed these systems had higher false-positive rates for students of color."))
rows.append(("What was the Wyze camera data exposure incident involving AI features?","In March 2022, Wyze confirmed a data breach where an employee error exposed a database containing emails, camera nicknames, WiFi SSIDs, and Alexa tokens of 2.4 million customers. The cameras used AI-powered person detection and event recording, meaning the breach also potentially exposed metadata about users' daily routines and home activities."))
rows.append(("How did researchers demonstrate membership inference attacks on ML models?","Shokri et al. introduced membership inference attacks in 2017, showing that given a trained ML model, an attacker could determine whether a specific data record was used in its training set. They achieved over 90% accuracy against ML-as-a-service platforms, revealing that ML models inherently leak information about their training data through their predictions."))
rows.append(("What happened in the facial recognition database breach at Biostar 2?","In August 2019, researchers at vpnMentor discovered that the Biostar 2 biometric security platform, used by thousands of organizations globally, had an unprotected database exposing 27.8 million records. The data included fingerprint data, facial recognition information, unencrypted usernames and passwords, and employee records from organizations across 83 countries."))
rows.append(("What privacy concerns arose from AI-powered email scanning?","Google faced class-action lawsuits over Gmail's AI-powered email scanning that analyzed email content for targeted advertising. While Google stopped ad-related scanning in 2017, the AI still scans emails for smart features. In 2021, an investigation revealed that Microsoft, Yahoo, and other providers also used AI to scan emails, raising ongoing privacy concerns about ML processing of communications."))
rows.append(("What was the Zoom AI training data controversy?","In August 2023, Zoom updated its terms of service to allow using customer data, including audio, video, and chat content, for training AI models. After massive public backlash from privacy advocates and customers, Zoom revised its terms within days to clarify it would not use customer content for AI training without explicit consent. The incident highlighted the tension between AI development and user privacy."))
rows.append(("How did a medical AI system expose patient data at a UK hospital?","In 2017, the UK Information Commissioner's Office ruled that the Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust had illegally shared 1.6 million patient records with Google DeepMind for development of a kidney injury detection app called Streams. The data sharing occurred without proper patient consent, violating the Data Protection Act and establishing a precedent for AI health data governance."))
rows.append(("What training data privacy issues were found in GitHub Copilot?","Researchers demonstrated in 2022 that GitHub Copilot could reproduce verbatim code snippets, API keys, and even personal information from its training data when given specific prompts. The tool was trained on public GitHub repositories, raising legal questions about code licensing, with a class-action lawsuit filed in November 2022 alleging violations of open-source licenses."))
rows.append(("What was the Verkada security camera AI breach?","In March 2021, a hacker collective accessed over 150,000 Verkada security cameras equipped with AI-powered facial recognition and person detection. The breach exposed live feeds from hospitals, prisons, schools, and Tesla factories. The hackers gained access through a super admin account exposed on the internet, demonstrating the risks of centralized AI surveillance infrastructure."))
rows.append(("How did the Equifax breach relate to AI security concerns?","The 2017 Equifax breach exposed personal data of 147 million people, and the stolen data was subsequently used to train fraudulent AI models for synthetic identity creation and automated credit fraud. This case demonstrated how breached data can be weaponized through AI to create second-order harms far beyond the original breach scope."))
rows.append(("What privacy issues arose with emotion recognition AI at schools?","In 2022, reports revealed that schools in China and some Western countries deployed emotion recognition AI cameras to monitor students' attention and emotional states during class. Privacy advocates raised alarms about collecting biometric emotion data from minors without meaningful consent, and studies questioned the scientific validity of emotion recognition technology with error rates above 30%."))
rows.append(("What was the OpenAI data leak via the ChatGPT API in 2023?","Security researchers discovered in mid-2023 that certain ChatGPT API calls could be manipulated to extract system prompts, revealing confidential instructions that companies had embedded in their ChatGPT-powered applications. This exposed proprietary business logic and custom safety instructions, demonstrating a new category of data leakage unique to LLM-based applications."))
rows.append(("How did the Strava heatmap reveal military base locations through AI analysis?","In January 2018, Strava published a global heatmap of user exercise activity tracked by AI-powered fitness features. Security analysts discovered the heatmap revealed the locations and layouts of secret military bases in Afghanistan, Syria, and other conflict zones, because soldiers' fitness tracking activities created visible patterns in otherwise dark areas of the map."))
rows.append(("What training data issues were discovered in LAION-5B used for Stable Diffusion?","In December 2023, the Stanford Internet Observatory found that LAION-5B, the massive image-text dataset used to train Stable Diffusion and other AI models, contained over 1,000 instances of child sexual abuse material (CSAM). LAION took the dataset offline immediately, and the discovery raised fundamental questions about the vetting processes for large-scale AI training datasets."))
rows.append(("What data exposure risks exist with AI coding assistants in enterprises?","A 2023 study by Cyberhaven found that 11% of data employees pasted into ChatGPT was confidential. Companies including JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, and Verizon banned or restricted employee use of generative AI tools to prevent data leakage. The risk extends beyond ChatGPT to all AI coding assistants that may transmit proprietary code to external servers for processing."))
rows.append(("How did voice AI training data raise privacy concerns at Amazon?","In 2019, Bloomberg revealed that Amazon employed thousands of workers worldwide to listen to and transcribe Alexa voice recordings to improve the AI. Workers reported hearing disturbing recordings including potential crimes, and the practice continued despite Amazon's privacy policy not clearly disclosing human review. Similar practices were later confirmed at Google, Apple, and Microsoft."))
rows.append(("What was the Clubhouse AI voice data scraping incident?","In April 2021, a SQL database containing data from 1.3 million Clubhouse users was found posted on a hacker forum. While Clubhouse claimed only public profile data was scraped, security researchers raised concerns that audio recordings processed by Clubhouse's AI features could be vulnerable to similar extraction, especially given the platform's recording of all conversations for trust and safety moderation."))
rows.append(("How did MoveIt Transfer vulnerability impact AI service providers?","The June 2023 MOVEit Transfer zero-day vulnerability (CVE-2023-34362) exploited by the Clop ransomware group affected multiple AI and data analytics companies. The breach chain exposed training data, model parameters, and customer datasets across organizations using the file transfer service, highlighting supply chain risks in AI infrastructure."))
rows.append(("What happened with the Meta AI training data and EU privacy regulations?","In June 2023, Meta announced plans to use Instagram and Facebook posts to train AI models but faced legal challenges under GDPR. The Irish Data Protection Commission ordered Meta to pause AI training on EU user data, and noyb (the European privacy advocacy group) filed complaints across 11 EU countries, demonstrating the regulatory friction between AI development and data protection laws."))
rows.append(("What was the LLM data extraction attack using divergence prompts?","In November 2023, researchers from Google DeepMind and universities demonstrated that asking ChatGPT to repeat a word forever (like 'poem poem poem...') caused it to diverge and emit memorized training data, including personal emails, phone numbers, and verbatim passages. This simple attack extracted several megabytes of training data from a production model, revealing a fundamental vulnerability."))
rows.append(("How did AI model theft occur through side-channel attacks?","Researchers at multiple universities demonstrated in 2023 that electromagnetic side-channel attacks on edge AI hardware could recover model architectures and weights. By analyzing power consumption patterns during inference on devices like the Google Coral Edge TPU, they reconstructed neural network structures with high accuracy, enabling intellectual property theft without any API access."))
rows.append(("What supply chain risks exist in AI model distribution through Hugging Face?","In 2023, security researchers found over 100 malicious ML models on Hugging Face that contained hidden backdoors and malware payloads. These models, disguised as popular architectures, could execute arbitrary code when loaded. Hugging Face implemented malware scanning, but the incident highlighted that the ML model supply chain faces similar risks to traditional software supply chains."))
rows.append(("What privacy risks were identified in federated learning for AI?","Despite being designed for privacy-preserving ML, researchers demonstrated in 2019 that federated learning gradient updates could be reversed to reconstruct individual training samples. Zhu et al. showed their Deep Leakage from Gradients (DLG) attack could recover training images pixel-by-pixel from shared gradients alone, undermining federated learning's privacy guarantees without additional protections like differential privacy."))

