# CATEGORY 5: AI in Cybercrime (35)
# =============================================================================
rows.append(("What is WormGPT and how is it used in cybercrime?","WormGPT emerged in July 2023 as a malicious LLM built on the GPT-J-6B model, specifically fine-tuned on malware-related data and sold on dark web forums. It was designed to generate phishing emails, malware code, and social engineering scripts without the ethical guardrails of commercial models. SlashNext researchers demonstrated it could produce highly convincing business email compromise attacks."))
rows.append(("What is FraudGPT and how does it differ from WormGPT?","FraudGPT appeared on dark web marketplaces in July 2023, advertised as a subscription-based tool ($200/month) for creating phishing pages, writing malicious code, finding vulnerabilities, and generating scam communications. Unlike WormGPT, FraudGPT was marketed as a more complete fraud toolkit and claimed to have been sold to over 3,000 buyers in its first weeks."))
rows.append(("How are AI-generated phishing campaigns more effective than traditional ones?","Studies by security firms in 2023 showed that AI-generated phishing emails had click-through rates 3-5 times higher than traditional template-based phishing. LLMs can generate grammatically perfect, contextually relevant phishing emails at scale, eliminating the spelling and grammatical errors that previously helped users identify phishing attempts. They can also personalize each email using scraped data about the target."))
rows.append(("How is AI being used for automated password cracking?","AI-powered password cracking tools like PassGAN, demonstrated in a 2023 Home Security Heroes study, can crack 51% of common passwords in under one minute and 71% in under a day. Unlike traditional rule-based crackers, AI models learn the distribution of real passwords from leaked databases and generate highly probable password candidates, making them significantly more effective against human-chosen passwords."))
rows.append(("How are cybercriminals using AI for automated vulnerability exploitation?","Researchers demonstrated in 2024 that LLMs like GPT-4 could autonomously exploit real-world vulnerabilities with a 87% success rate when given the CVE description and access to a target system. AI agents can chain multiple exploitation steps, adapt to different system configurations, and even write custom exploit code, potentially democratizing advanced exploitation capabilities."))
rows.append(("How is AI-assisted social engineering evolving?","AI has transformed social engineering by enabling attackers to generate highly personalized pretexting scenarios at scale. Tools can analyze a target's social media presence, professional history, and communication style to craft tailored approaches. A 2023 IBM X-Force study found AI-crafted phishing messages were nearly indistinguishable from human-written ones in blind testing by security professionals."))
rows.append(("What is polymorphic malware using LLMs?","Security researchers at HYAS demonstrated in early 2023 that LLMs could generate polymorphic malware—code that constantly changes its appearance while maintaining its malicious functionality. Their proof-of-concept, BlackMamba, used ChatGPT API calls at runtime to generate new obfuscated keylogger payloads each time it executed, evading every endpoint detection tool tested against it."))
rows.append(("How is synthetic identity fraud using AI at scale?","Synthetic identity fraud, where AI combines real and fabricated personal data to create fake identities, cost US financial institutions an estimated $6 billion in 2023 according to the Federal Reserve. AI generates realistic-looking documents, creates consistent digital footprints, and can maintain multiple synthetic identities simultaneously, making detection exponentially more difficult than traditional identity theft."))
rows.append(("How are cybercriminals using AI for reconnaissance and OSINT?","AI-powered tools can automate open-source intelligence gathering, scraping and analyzing social media profiles, corporate websites, and public records to build detailed target profiles in minutes instead of days. Tools demonstrated at security conferences can map entire organizational hierarchies, identify key decision-makers, and find potential security weaknesses by analyzing publicly available information."))
rows.append(("What role does AI play in business email compromise (BEC) attacks?","AI has supercharged BEC attacks by enabling real-time email composition that mimics the writing style of compromised executives. The FBI reported BEC losses of $2.7 billion in 2022, and AI-enhanced attacks in 2023-2024 showed increased success rates. LLMs can analyze an executive's previous emails and replicate their tone, vocabulary, and formatting to create near-perfect impersonations."))
rows.append(("How are AI-powered tools being used to bypass CAPTCHAs?","AI models can now solve most CAPTCHA types including image recognition, text distortion, and audio CAPTCHAs with accuracy rates above 95%. Services offering AI CAPTCHA solving charge as little as $0.50 per 1,000 solutions. The development of vision-language models has made even complex CAPTCHAs like 'identify all traffic lights' solvable, forcing CAPTCHA providers to develop increasingly complex behavioral analysis."))
rows.append(("How is AI used in automated credential stuffing attacks?","AI enhances credential stuffing by predicting password variations users might employ across different services. Rather than simply replaying leaked credentials, AI models generate likely password mutations (adding numbers, changing capitalization, substituting characters) based on patterns learned from billions of leaked passwords, increasing the success rate of attacks against accounts where users reuse modified passwords."))
rows.append(("What is the role of AI in creating convincing fake websites for phishing?","AI tools can now generate entire convincing replica websites in minutes, including dynamic content, proper branding, and even functional chatbots that mimic customer service interactions. Groups like Scattered Spider have used AI to create pixel-perfect clones of corporate login pages with realistic SSL certificates, making visual detection nearly impossible for untrained users."))
rows.append(("How are AI-generated voices being used in vishing attacks?","Voice phishing (vishing) attacks using AI-cloned voices increased 350% in 2023 according to a Pindrop report. Attackers clone executive or IT support voices from public recordings and use them in real-time phone calls to request password resets, wire transfers, or sensitive information. The average cost of a successful AI-powered vishing attack reached $14 million for enterprise targets."))
rows.append(("What is AI-powered malware evasion?","AI-driven malware uses machine learning to analyze the sandbox environments used by security tools and modifies its behavior accordingly. The malware learns to detect when it is being analyzed (sandbox evasion), generates new obfuscation patterns to avoid signature detection, and can time its malicious activities to evade behavioral analysis windows."))
rows.append(("How are darknet markets using AI for drug synthesis and precursor identification?","AI chemistry models have been repurposed on darknet forums to identify novel drug synthesis pathways using legal precursors and predict which chemical modifications might evade current drug scheduling laws. A 2023 study by Collaborations Pharmaceuticals demonstrated their AI drug discovery tool could generate 40,000 potential chemical weapon compounds in six hours, highlighting dual-use risks."))
rows.append(("How is AI enabling automated exploitation of zero-day vulnerabilities?","AI systems can analyze software binaries and source code to discover potential vulnerabilities faster than human researchers. At DEF CON 2023, DARPA's AIxCC competition showcased AI systems that could find and exploit novel vulnerabilities. While primarily developed for defense, the same techniques are available to offensive actors, potentially accelerating the discovery of zero-day exploits."))
rows.append(("What is the threat of AI-generated disinformation campaigns for hire?","Commercial disinformation-as-a-service operations now use AI to generate and distribute fake news articles, social media posts, and comments at scale. A 2024 OpenAI report identified five state-linked operations using their models for influence campaigns. These operations can generate thousands of unique, contextually appropriate posts per hour across multiple languages and platforms."))
rows.append(("How are AI chatbots being weaponized for social engineering at scale?","Attackers deploy AI chatbots on social media and messaging platforms that engage targets in extended conversations to build trust before executing scams. These bots can maintain coherent long-term conversations, adapt to user responses, and gradually steer conversations toward credential theft or financial fraud, operating thousands of simultaneous conversations at minimal cost."))
rows.append(("What is the risk of AI-powered supply chain attacks?","AI enables more sophisticated software supply chain attacks by analyzing open-source dependencies to identify high-impact targets, generating malicious code that passes automated review, and creating convincing commit histories for fake contributor accounts. Security researchers at Checkmarx demonstrated in 2023 that AI could generate malicious Python packages with names similar to popular libraries, exploiting typosquatting."))
rows.append(("How is AI being used in ransomware operations?","Ransomware groups are using AI for target selection (identifying organizations most likely to pay), customizing ransom notes for maximum psychological impact, automating lateral movement within networks, and optimizing encryption routines. The MOVEit attack by Clop in 2023 showed signs of AI-assisted victim profiling, with ransom demands calibrated to each victim's financial capacity."))
rows.append(("What are AI-powered network intrusion tools?","AI-enhanced penetration testing tools like PentestGPT can autonomously scan networks, identify vulnerabilities, and chain exploits. While developed for legitimate security testing, these tools lower the skill barrier for attackers. A 2024 study showed GPT-4 could perform 73% of common penetration testing tasks when given appropriate tools and network access."))
rows.append(("How are criminals using AI for document forgery?","AI generates increasingly convincing forged documents including passports, driver's licenses, bank statements, and medical records. The technology can match fonts, security features, and paper textures from reference images. Financial institutions reported a 40% increase in AI-generated fraudulent documents in 2023, with some forgeries sophisticated enough to pass initial automated document verification checks."))
rows.append(("What is the role of AI in cryptocurrency fraud?","AI is used in cryptocurrency scams for creating fake trading platforms with convincing AI-generated market data, deploying chatbots that impersonate crypto advisors, generating deepfake endorsements from celebrities, and building sophisticated pump-and-dump schemes. The FTC reported over $1.4 billion in crypto fraud losses in 2023, with AI-enhanced schemes showing higher success rates."))
rows.append(("How are AI-generated code reviews being exploited?","Attackers have exploited AI code review tools by crafting pull requests with malicious code designed to appear benign to automated AI reviewers. The malicious code uses patterns that AI models associate with legitimate programming constructs while hiding backdoors in logic that is difficult for automated systems to assess for intent, bypassing AI-assisted code review processes."))
rows.append(("What is the threat of autonomous AI hacking agents?","Researchers at UIUC demonstrated in 2024 that teams of LLM agents could collaborate to hack websites, with GPT-4 achieving a 73% success rate on real-world web vulnerabilities. These autonomous agents can plan multi-step attacks, retry with different approaches when blocked, and adapt to defensive measures, raising concerns about fully automated cyber attacks."))
rows.append(("How is AI enabling more targeted spear-phishing of executives?","AI tools scrape LinkedIn profiles, press releases, SEC filings, and social media to build comprehensive profiles of C-suite targets. They then generate hyper-personalized spear-phishing emails referencing real events, relationships, and business contexts. Security firm Abnormal Security reported a 130% increase in AI-crafted executive-targeted emails in 2023 compared to the previous year."))
rows.append(("What is the risk of AI-powered insider threat detection evasion?","AI enables malicious insiders to evade behavior-based detection systems by learning the patterns that trigger alerts and modifying their activities accordingly. Adversarial machine learning techniques can be used to gradually shift behavior baselines, making data exfiltration appear as normal activity. This represents an AI-vs-AI arms race between detection and evasion."))
rows.append(("How are AI models being used to generate exploit code from vulnerability descriptions?","Research published in 2024 showed that frontier LLMs could generate working exploit code for known CVEs with increasing reliability. When given a vulnerability description from the National Vulnerability Database, GPT-4 successfully generated functional exploits for 87% of tested CVEs, reducing the time from vulnerability disclosure to weaponization from days or weeks to minutes."))
rows.append(("What is the scale of AI-assisted financial fraud globally?","Global AI-assisted financial fraud losses were estimated at $25 billion in 2023, up from $17 billion in 2022, according to Juniper Research. The largest growth areas were synthetic identity fraud, AI-enhanced payment fraud, and deepfake-assisted wire transfer scams. Financial institutions spent an estimated $10 billion on AI-based fraud detection in 2023, creating an AI-versus-AI landscape."))
rows.append(("How are threat actors using LLMs for malware development?","Microsoft and OpenAI reported in February 2024 that state-linked threat actors from Russia (Forest Blizzard), China (Charcoal Typhoon), Iran (Crimson Sandstorm), and North Korea (Emerald Sleet) were using LLMs for scripting, reconnaissance, vulnerability research, and social engineering content. While no novel malware was generated, the LLMs significantly accelerated traditional attack workflows."))

# =============================================================================
# CATEGORY 6: Regulatory Responses (30)
# =============================================================================
rows.append(("What is the EU AI Act and when was it enacted?","The EU AI Act was formally adopted by the European Parliament on March 13, 2024, becoming the world's first comprehensive AI regulation. It categorizes AI systems by risk level (unacceptable, high, limited, minimal) and imposes requirements proportional to risk, including bans on social scoring and real-time biometric surveillance, with full enforcement phased in between 2024 and 2027."))
rows.append(("What are the key enforcement mechanisms of the EU AI Act?","The EU AI Act imposes fines up to 35 million euros or 7% of global annual turnover for the most serious violations. It created the European AI Office to oversee enforcement and established regulatory sandboxes for innovation. High-risk AI systems must undergo conformity assessments, maintain technical documentation, and implement human oversight mechanisms before deployment."))
rows.append(("What did the US Executive Order on AI Safety (October 2023) require?","President Biden's Executive Order 14110, signed October 30, 2023, required developers of powerful AI models to share safety test results with the government, directed NIST to develop AI safety standards, and established guidelines for AI use in government. It required reporting of training runs using computing power above certain thresholds and mandated red-team testing for dual-use foundation models."))
rows.append(("What are China's AI regulations and their unique features?","China has enacted multiple targeted AI regulations: the Algorithmic Recommendation Regulation (March 2022), Deep Synthesis Provisions requiring deepfake labeling (January 2023), and Interim Generative AI Measures (August 2023). China's approach uniquely requires that AI-generated content aligns with 'core socialist values' and mandates security assessments before launching public-facing AI services."))
rows.append(("What is the UK AI Safety Institute and its role?","The UK AI Safety Institute (AISI), announced at the Bletchley Park AI Safety Summit in November 2023, was the world's first government-backed AI safety research body. It conducts pre-deployment evaluations of frontier AI models, researches AI risks, and develops safety testing methodologies. AISI established a partnership with its US counterpart and has tested models from OpenAI, Anthropic, and Meta."))
rows.append(("What is the NIST AI Risk Management Framework?","NIST released the AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0) in January 2023, providing voluntary guidance for managing AI risks across the lifecycle. It is organized around four core functions: Govern, Map, Measure, and Manage. The framework has been adopted by many US organizations as a best-practice standard and influenced the Biden Executive Order's approach to AI safety."))
rows.append(("What is the Frontier Model Forum and what has it achieved?","The Frontier Model Forum was established in July 2023 by Anthropic, Google, Microsoft, and OpenAI as an industry self-regulatory body for AI safety. It funds safety research through a $10 million AI Safety Fund, develops best practices for responsible frontier model development, and promotes sharing of safety information. Critics argue it lacks binding commitments and enforcement mechanisms."))
rows.append(("What is the Partnership on AI and its contributions?","The Partnership on AI, founded in 2016 by Amazon, Apple, DeepMind, Facebook, Google, IBM, and Microsoft, is a multi-stakeholder organization developing AI best practices. It has published frameworks on responsible AI publication norms, synthetic media guidelines, and AI's impact on workers. While influential in setting norms, its recommendations remain voluntary and lack enforcement power."))
rows.append(("How has the FTC approached AI regulation in the United States?","The FTC has used existing consumer protection and competition laws to regulate AI, issuing warnings about AI-enabled deception and taking enforcement actions. In 2023, it opened investigations into OpenAI and multiple AI companies for data practices and false claims. The FTC's approach treats AI harms as existing consumer protection violations, applying established legal frameworks to new technologies."))
rows.append(("What AI regulations has Canada implemented?","Canada introduced the Artificial Intelligence and Data Act (AIDA) as part of Bill C-27, proposing a risk-based regulatory framework for AI. The bill, introduced in 2022, mandates assessments of high-impact AI systems, requires mitigation of biased output, and proposes criminal penalties for reckless AI deployment causing serious harm. The bill had not yet passed as of early 2024."))
rows.append(("How has Brazil approached AI regulation?","Brazil's Senate approved an AI regulatory framework (Bill 2338/2023) in December 2024 based on a rights-based approach. It establishes a risk classification system similar to the EU AI Act, creates an AI supervisory authority, and requires impact assessments for high-risk AI systems. Brazil's approach emphasizes protecting fundamental rights and addressing algorithmic discrimination."))
rows.append(("What is the Bletchley Declaration on AI safety?","The Bletchley Declaration, signed on November 1, 2023 by 28 countries including the US, UK, China, and EU nations at the UK AI Safety Summit, was the first international agreement on AI safety. It acknowledged the potentially catastrophic risks from frontier AI, endorsed the need for international cooperation on AI safety testing, and established a framework for future summits in Seoul and Paris."))
rows.append(("How has the SEC addressed AI-related risks in financial markets?","The SEC proposed rules in 2023 requiring broker-dealers and investment advisers to address conflicts of interest associated with their use of AI and predictive analytics. SEC Chair Gary Gensler warned about systemic financial risks from concentrated AI model dependency and AI-driven herding behavior in markets, and the SEC took enforcement actions against companies making misleading AI claims (AI washing)."))
rows.append(("What AI safety commitments did major companies make at the White House?","In July 2023, seven leading AI companies (Amazon, Anthropic, Google, Inflection, Meta, Microsoft, OpenAI) made voluntary commitments at the White House including watermarking AI-generated content, sharing safety information, and investing in cybersecurity. Eight more companies joined in September 2023. Critics noted these commitments were voluntary and lacked specific metrics or enforcement mechanisms."))
rows.append(("How has Japan positioned itself on AI regulation?","Japan has taken a relatively permissive approach to AI regulation, with the government stating in 2023 that it would not immediately impose strict regulations similar to the EU AI Act. Japan's approach emphasizes innovation-friendly guidelines through its AI Strategy Council, though it updated copyright guidance in 2023 to clarify that AI training on copyrighted material may not always qualify as fair use."))
rows.append(("What is the IEEE's role in AI ethics standardization?","IEEE has developed multiple AI ethics standards including IEEE 7000 (ethical design), IEEE 7001 (transparency), IEEE 7002 (data privacy), and IEEE 7010 (wellbeing metrics). The IEEE Global Initiative on Ethics of Autonomous and Intelligent Systems, launched in 2016, has published the Ethically Aligned Design framework and created certification programs for ethical AI development practices."))
rows.append(("How has India approached AI governance?","India has taken a light-touch approach to AI regulation, with NITI Aayog publishing the National Strategy for AI in 2018. In March 2024, India's IT Ministry issued an advisory requiring government approval before launching AI models in India, which was later softened to apply only to unreliable or unverified AI platforms. India has positioned itself as seeking to balance innovation with safety."))
rows.append(("What is the role of the OECD AI Principles?","The OECD AI Principles, adopted in May 2019 by 42 countries, were the first intergovernmental AI standards. They promote AI that is innovative, trustworthy, respects human rights, and is transparent, robust, and accountable. The principles influenced subsequent regulations globally, including the EU AI Act and the G20 AI Principles, and established the OECD AI Policy Observatory for implementation monitoring."))
rows.append(("How has Singapore's AI governance model been received internationally?","Singapore's Model AI Governance Framework, released in 2019 and updated in 2020, has been praised for its pragmatic, industry-friendly approach. It provides practical guidance on explainability, transparency, and human oversight without imposing rigid regulations. The framework, along with Singapore's AI Verify testing toolkit launched in 2022, has influenced AI governance approaches across Southeast Asia."))
rows.append(("What AI-specific privacy regulations have emerged globally?","The intersection of AI and privacy has led to specific regulatory actions: GDPR's Article 22 restricts automated decision-making, the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA) added automated decision-making provisions in 2023, and the Colorado AI Act (signed 2024) specifically addresses algorithmic discrimination. These laws require transparency about AI use in decisions affecting individuals and provide opt-out rights."))
rows.append(("How has the EU AI Act's ban on social scoring been implemented?","The EU AI Act explicitly bans AI-powered social scoring systems by public authorities, including systems that evaluate trustworthiness based on social behavior or personality characteristics. This provision, one of the first to take effect (six months after adoption), was directly inspired by concerns about China's social credit systems and prevents similar systems from being deployed in the EU."))
rows.append(("What regulatory challenges exist for open-source AI models?","Open-source AI models present unique regulatory challenges because once released, they cannot be recalled or restricted. The EU AI Act's final text exempted most open-source models from stringent requirements unless they pose systemic risks, but debates continue about whether this exemption is appropriate. The tension between open-source benefits (transparency, research access) and risks (misuse, lack of control) remains unresolved."))
rows.append(("How have financial regulators addressed AI risk in banking?","The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision, the OCC, and the Fed have issued guidance on AI risk management for banks, focusing on model risk management (SR 11-7), fair lending compliance, and third-party AI vendor oversight. In 2023, the OCC highlighted AI concentration risk—the danger that many banks relying on the same AI models could create correlated failures during market stress."))
rows.append(("What is the current state of international AI governance coordination?","International AI governance coordination remains fragmented despite the Bletchley Declaration. Different jurisdictions have adopted varying approaches: the EU favors regulation, the US relies on executive orders and existing frameworks, China imposes content-specific requirements, and many nations take wait-and-see approaches. The UN established a High-Level Advisory Body on AI in 2023 to work toward global governance principles."))
rows.append(("How has the healthcare sector been specifically regulated for AI?","The FDA has authorized over 700 AI/ML-enabled medical devices as of 2024, developing a framework for Software as a Medical Device (SaMD). The FDA's 2021 action plan addressed continuous learning AI systems, and the WHO issued guidance on AI ethics and governance in health in 2021. Key requirements include clinical validation, algorithmic transparency, and post-market surveillance for AI-based diagnostics."))
rows.append(("What regulatory actions have been taken against AI bias in hiring?","New York City's Local Law 144, effective July 2023, requires annual bias audits for AI tools used in hiring decisions. The EEOC has issued guidance clarifying that AI-driven hiring discrimination violates Title VII. Illinois and Maryland have enacted laws requiring consent for AI video interview analysis. These represent the first wave of regulations specifically targeting AI in employment decisions."))
rows.append(("How are autonomous weapons being regulated internationally?","Discussions on autonomous weapons systems at the UN Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons have been ongoing since 2013 without producing binding regulation. Over 30 countries support banning fully autonomous weapons, but major military powers including the US, Russia, and China resist binding restrictions. The ICRC has called for new legally binding rules to ensure human control over the use of force by AI systems."))
rows.append(("What is the current state of AI liability frameworks?","The EU proposed an AI Liability Directive in September 2022 to complement the AI Act, establishing rules for civil liability claims related to AI. It introduces a rebuttable presumption of causality for non-compliant AI systems, easing the burden of proof for victims. In the US, liability for AI harms remains governed by existing product liability, negligence, and contract law, with no AI-specific federal liability framework."))
rows.append(("How has content authenticity regulation evolved in response to AI?","Multiple jurisdictions have mandated disclosure of AI-generated content. China requires visible watermarks on all synthetic content since January 2023. The EU AI Act requires disclosure when interacting with AI systems and labeling deepfakes. US states including California and Texas have enacted laws against AI-generated election disinformation. Industry standards like C2PA provide technical infrastructure for content provenance."))
rows.append(("What enforcement actions have been taken for AI safety violations?","Italy's Data Protection Authority temporarily banned ChatGPT in March 2023 over GDPR concerns, requiring OpenAI to implement age verification and privacy disclosures before lifting the ban. The FTC issued cease-and-desist orders to companies making fraudulent AI claims. The UK ICO fined Clearview AI 7.5 million pounds. These early enforcement actions established that existing regulations apply to AI systems and set precedents for future cases."))

